.ce
\fBURLs\fR

.in 4
One of the core concepts of Cynosure 2 is \fBeverything is a URL\fR.  This document lists all the built-in schemes.

.in 6
\fBfile:\fR
.in 8
The most important scheme.  All file access is done through this scheme.  If no scheme is specified in the call to \fB\mbopen\m[default]\fR, this is the scheme that is used.

.in 6
\fBkernel:\fR
.in 8
Used to retrieve some information about the kernel (e.g. version, uptime).

.in 6
\fBblock:\fR
.in 8
Stores all registered block devices.

.in 6
\fBtty:\fR
.in 8
All registered TTY devices are under this scheme.


.ce
\fBOptional Schemes\fR

.in 4
These schemes are included by configuration options.

.in 6
\fBcomponent:\fR
.in 8
All components are under this scheme.  They can be opened with \fBcomponent\fR://\fBaddress\fR.

.in 6
\fBexec:\fR
.in 8
Used to register custom executable formats.  To register \fBvelx\fR files:
.in 10
- Call \fB\mbopen\m[default]\fR(\fB\mr"exec://velx"\m[default]\fR)
.in 10
- Call \fB\mbioctl\m[default]\fR with the returned file descriptor to change some attributes of the executable:
.in 12
* \fB\mr"setMode"\m[default]\fR with a boolean value specifying whether to determine the file type by extension or by a magic number.
* \fB\mr"setInterpreter"\m[default]\fR with the path to the executable's interpreter.

.in 6
\fBtcp:\fR
.in 8
Used to open TCP connections.

.in 6
\fBhttp:\fR, \fBhttps:\fR
.in 8
Used to open HTTP and HTTPS connections.

.in 6
\fBcftp:\fR
.in 8
Used to wrap other URLs in the Cynosure File Transfer Protocol.  To wrap a \fBtcp:\fR connection with this:
.in 12
\fBcftp://\mytcp://example.com\m[default]\fR

.in 6
\fBmtel:\fR
.in 8
Open Minitel sockets.

.in 6
\fBgert:\fR
.in 8
Open GERTi sockets.
